transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for having me. I'm happy to share my experiences and insights. Please go ahead with your questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Olivia, and I'm 52 years old. I own a small business here in San Francisco, which keeps me quite busy. I have a bachelor's degree, and I feel fortunate to have good healthcare access through my private insurance. I’m single and, while I’m not planning on having any more children, I have four kids from previous pregnancies. I manage my type 2 diabetes with medication, and I try to stay active, although I don't exercise as regularly as I’d like. Socially, I do find it a bit challenging to connect with others, which sometimes leads to feelings of isolation. But overall, I'm doing well and focused on my health and my business.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Certainly! I first learned I was pregnant when I was in my early twenties. I remember it quite vividly. I had just finished college and was starting to build my career. I found out I was pregnant with my first child after missing my period and decided to take a home pregnancy test. It was a big surprise, but I was excited and nervous at the same time. 

Over the years, I had a total of four pregnancies. Thankfully, they were all uncomplicated vaginal deliveries, which I'm very grateful for. Each pregnancy brought its own set of challenges, but I was fortunate to have supportive healthcare providers who guided me through the process. I also had one elective abortion during that time, which was a difficult decision but one that I felt was right for me at the time. 

Now that I reflect on those experiences, I realize how much I learned about myself and my body through each pregnancy. Is there anything specific you would like to know about my pregnancies or the care I received?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care as soon as I confirmed my pregnancy with my first child. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and apprehension about the whole process. I scheduled my first appointment with an OB-GYN shortly after taking the home pregnancy test. 

The experience was generally positive. My doctor was very supportive and took the time to answer all my questions, which helped alleviate some of my worries. They conducted the necessary tests and ultrasounds, and I felt reassured by the regular check-ups. I appreciated the educational resources they provided about what to expect during pregnancy, and I was encouraged to maintain a healthy lifestyle, which was particularly important for me since I was just starting to manage my health with a focus on diabetes.

In subsequent pregnancies, I continued to seek care early on and had similar experiences with my healthcare providers. They were always attentive to my medical history, especially regarding my type 2 diabetes, and ensured that my condition was well-managed throughout the pregnancies. 

Overall, I felt well cared for during my prenatal visits, and I was grateful for the access to healthcare that allowed me to have those experiences. Is there any aspect of prenatal care you'd like to delve deeper into?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I provided my prenatal care primarily through an OB-GYN practice that I was referred to by my primary care physician. Over the years, I developed a relationship with a few different doctors within that practice. Each of them was knowledgeable and attentive, which helped me feel comfortable discussing my health concerns, especially relating to my type 2 diabetes. 

I appreciated that they were familiar with my medical history and aware of my specific needs during pregnancy. They always took the time to listen to my questions and concerns, which made me feel valued as a patient. I felt that I could openly discuss any issues I was facing, whether they were related to my diabetes management or general pregnancy-related queries.

While I had a good rapport with my doctors, I did notice that the practice sometimes felt a bit busy, and there were times when I wished for a bit more one-on-one time. However, I understood the demands of their workload and felt they did their best to provide quality care. 

Currently, I’m not seeking prenatal care, given that I’m not planning any more pregnancies. However, I do maintain regular check-ups with my primary care physician to manage my diabetes and overall health. If you have specific questions about my experiences with my healthcare providers or any particular aspect of that relationship, I’d be happy to share more.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I can definitely describe that for you! During my pregnancies, I had prenatal appointments typically every four weeks during the first trimester, which then increased to every two weeks as I moved into the third trimester, and finally weekly as I approached my due date. 

A typical visit would usually start with a check-in with the nurse who would take my vitals—things like my blood pressure, weight, and sometimes my blood sugar levels, especially since I have type 2 diabetes. They would also ask about any symptoms or concerns I might be experiencing.

After that, I would meet with my OB-GYN. They would review my medical history, ask about my diabetes management, and discuss how I was feeling overall. I appreciated that they always seemed genuinely interested in my well-being, and I felt comfortable sharing any concerns, whether they were about my diabetes or just general pregnancy worries.

They would often perform an ultrasound to monitor the baby's development and check for any potential issues. I found those moments particularly exciting, as it was always reassuring to see the baby and hear the heartbeat. They would take the time to explain what they were looking for and answer any questions I had about the images on the screen.

Towards the end of the appointment, they would provide me with educational materials about what to expect in the coming weeks, any necessary lifestyle adjustments I should consider, and they would reinforce the importance of nutrition and exercise for managing my diabetes during pregnancy. 

Overall, I felt that each visit was thorough and informative, and I left each time feeling more empowered about my health and my baby's well-being. Is there a specific element of these appointments you'd like to explore further?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I’m grateful to say that I didn’t experience any significant health concerns or complications during my pregnancies. Each of my four pregnancies was uncomplicated, which I know is a blessing. However, managing my type 2 diabetes was certainly a focus throughout each pregnancy. 

My healthcare providers were attentive to my blood sugar levels and made adjustments to my medication as needed to ensure that my diabetes was well-controlled. They monitored my health closely, especially because I was aware that uncontrolled diabetes can pose risks during pregnancy. I was proactive about following their recommendations regarding diet and exercise, which I believe contributed to my positive outcomes.

That said, there were some moments of concern where I had to be more vigilant about my health. For instance, there were times when my blood sugar levels were harder to manage due to hormonal changes, and I had to make adjustments to my diet and monitor my levels more frequently. But with the support of my healthcare team, I felt equipped to handle those challenges.

I also appreciated that my doctors were always ready to discuss any potential risks or complications, which helped me stay informed and prepared. If there’s anything specific you’d like to know about managing health concerns or how I navigated those discussions with my providers, I’d be happy to elaborate.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Currently, I take several medications to manage my type 2 diabetes. I’m on a metformin regimen, which has been effective for me in controlling my blood sugar levels. My doctor has adjusted the dosage over the years to align with my health needs, particularly during my pregnancies, but I continue to take it now to maintain stable blood glucose levels.

In addition to metformin, I also take a daily multivitamin to ensure I’m getting adequate nutrients, especially since I’ve been more health-conscious lately. I try to focus on my overall wellness, and I find that taking a multivitamin helps me feel more balanced. 

I don’t take any specific supplements beyond that, but I do pay attention to my diet and make sure I’m eating a variety of foods to support my health. If you’re interested in more details about my medication management or any dietary adjustments I've made, I’d be glad to share!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was quite mindful of my diet and nutrition, especially with my type 2 diabetes to consider. I focused on maintaining a balanced diet that would support both my health and the development of my baby. 

In general, I aimed to eat a variety of whole foods, including plenty of fruits and vegetables, lean proteins, whole grains, and healthy fats. I tried to keep my carbohydrate intake balanced to manage my blood sugar levels effectively. My healthcare providers emphasized the importance of monitoring my carb intake, so I paid attention to portion sizes and the types of carbohydrates I consumed, opting for complex carbs when possible.

I also incorporated more fiber into my diet, which helped with digestion and blood sugar control. Foods like oatmeal, beans, and leafy greens became staples for me. Additionally, I made sure to stay hydrated, drinking plenty of water throughout the day.

During my pregnancies, I experienced cravings, like many women do, and I found it helpful to allow myself to indulge in moderation. I learned that it was okay to enjoy treats occasionally, but I tried to balance those moments with healthier choices.

I also had regular check-ins with a nutritionist who specialized in maternal health. They provided me with valuable guidance on meal planning and snacks to keep my blood sugar stable. This support was essential, especially as my body was going through so many changes during pregnancy.

Overall, I felt that by being proactive about my diet and nutrition, I was able to support my health and the health of my babies. If you’d like to know more about specific dietary choices I made or how I managed any challenges related to food during my pregnancies, I’d be happy to elaborate further.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I experienced a mix of emotions, which I think is quite common for many women. Initially, there was a lot of excitement and joy as I anticipated bringing a new life into the world. However, I also faced moments of anxiety and concern, especially regarding my health and managing my type 2 diabetes.

As my pregnancies progressed, I found that my emotions fluctuated. There were days when I felt overwhelmed by the changes happening in my body and the responsibilities of becoming a parent. I often worried about how my diabetes might affect my pregnancy and my baby's health. It was a constant balancing act, and I sometimes felt stressed about managing my blood sugar levels alongside the typical pregnancy challenges.

I did my best to stay positive, and I leaned on my support system—friends, family, and my healthcare providers—who were there to listen and offer reassurance. My doctors were particularly encouraging and made it a point to discuss not just my physical health but also my emotional well-being during the visits. They provided resources for coping with stress and managing anxiety, which I found helpful.

I also sought out some prenatal classes, which allowed me to connect with other expecting mothers. Sharing experiences with them helped alleviate some of my feelings of isolation and gave me a sense of community. 

Overall, I felt a range of emotions throughout my pregnancies, but I always tried to focus on the joy and anticipation of welcoming my children. If you're interested in exploring specific emotional experiences or coping strategies I used during this time, I'd be happy to share more about that.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I had a support network that was quite important to me during my pregnancies. While I was single, I relied heavily on my family and close friends for support. My parents were incredibly supportive and offered to help out whenever I needed it, whether that meant accompanying me to doctor’s appointments or simply being there to listen when I had concerns. They were always excited about the prospect of becoming grandparents, which added to the joy of my pregnancies.

I also had a close group of friends, some of whom were also mothers. They provided a great source of camaraderie and understanding. We would often share experiences and advice, which made me feel less isolated in my journey. I appreciated their honesty about the challenges of motherhood, which helped me prepare for what was ahead.

In addition to my family and friends, I found a strong support system through my healthcare providers. They not only addressed my medical needs but also took the time to check in on my emotional well-being. I remember one doctor in particular who was wonderful about encouraging me to express any fears or anxieties I had. 

Lastly, I participated in prenatal classes where I met other expecting mothers. That was a significant part of my support system, as we shared our experiences and concerns, which helped me feel connected to others going through similar journeys.

Overall, I felt fortunate to have a robust support network. It made a difference in how I navigated my pregnancies, especially during moments of stress or uncertainty. If you’d like to know more about specific instances of support or how I managed my relationships during that time, I’d be happy to share further.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did think quite a bit about my birth plan and what my preferences were for delivery. Since I had previously experienced uncomplicated vaginal deliveries, I felt comfortable with that approach and hoped to maintain that consistency. My priority was always the health and safety of my baby and myself, so I was open to making adjustments as needed based on the circumstances at the time.

I preferred to have a natural delivery without unnecessary medical interventions, unless they were necessary for the health of me or my baby. I valued the idea of being able to move around during labor and have a supportive environment where I could feel relaxed. I often discussed my preferences with my healthcare providers during my prenatal appointments, and they were very supportive of my choices, which was reassuring.

I also considered aspects like having a quiet and calm environment during labor, along with having my support network present. My parents were always eager to be there for me, and I appreciated having familiar faces around to help me feel more at ease during such an intense experience.

That said, I understood that childbirth can be unpredictable, and I was prepared to adapt my birth plan if needed. For example, if complications arose that required medical intervention, I was ready to accept that for the safety of my baby. I felt empowered by being informed and engaged in the planning process, and I trusted my healthcare team to guide me through any necessary changes.

If you have specific questions about my birth plan preferences or the discussions I had with my healthcare providers regarding delivery, I’d be happy to share more details!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I utilized a variety of sources to gather information about pregnancy and childbirth. I wanted to be as informed as possible, especially given my type 2 diabetes and the specific considerations that came with it.

First and foremost, I relied heavily on my healthcare providers. They provided a wealth of information during my prenatal visits, and I appreciated the educational materials they shared. They would often recommend specific books and websites that were reliable and evidence-based. I felt comfortable asking questions and discussing any topics that I was unsure about.

In addition to advice from my doctors, I read several books on pregnancy and childbirth. Some of my favorites included “What to Expect When You're Expecting” and “The Mayo Clinic Guide to a Healthy Pregnancy.” These books offered practical advice and covered a wide range of topics, from nutrition to labor and delivery.

I also sought out online resources, particularly websites from reputable health organizations like the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) and the March of Dimes. These sites provided up-to-date information and research, which helped me understand the latest guidelines and best practices.

Furthermore, I attended prenatal classes that were offered in my community. These classes were not only informative but also allowed me to connect with other expectant mothers. We shared experiences, concerns, and tips, which made me feel less isolated and more supported.

Lastly, I found value in online forums and support groups where women shared their pregnancy stories and advice. It was helpful to hear from others who were going through similar experiences, although I was always careful to verify any information I found online with my healthcare providers.

Overall, I aimed to gather information from a range of sources to ensure I was well-prepared. If you'd like to know more about specific topics I researched or how I evaluated the information I found, please let me know!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was fortunate to have good financial stability due to my small business and private health insurance, which significantly alleviated some of the financial stress associated with having a baby. I had a solid understanding of my healthcare coverage, and my insurance plan covered most prenatal care and delivery costs, which was a relief.

To manage the financial aspects of pregnancy, I created a budget that accounted for medical expenses, baby supplies, and other related costs. I carefully tracked my spending and made adjustments as needed to ensure I was prepared for any unexpected expenses. This included things like co-pays for doctor visits, prenatal vitamins, and any additional medical supplies I might need.

I also looked into various resources and programs that could provide additional support. For example, I explored local programs that offered assistance with baby supplies, such as diapers and clothing, which helped alleviate some of the costs associated with welcoming a new child. Additionally, I set up a savings account specifically for baby-related expenses, which helped me stay organized and focused on my financial goals.

I also spoke with other mothers and friends who had gone through similar experiences to gather insights on budgeting and financial planning for a baby. Hearing their stories and tips helped me feel more prepared and less overwhelmed.

Overall, I felt that by being proactive about my financial planning and utilizing the resources available to me, I was able to navigate the costs associated with pregnancy and preparing for a baby more confidently. If you have specific questions about any financial resources I used or how I approached certain expenses, I would be happy to elaborate further.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I found that balancing work and the demands of pregnancy could be a bit challenging, but I was fortunate to be a small business owner, which allowed me some flexibility. I was able to manage my schedule and adjust my workload as needed, which made it easier to prioritize my health and well-being during that time.

In the early stages of my pregnancies, I focused on maintaining my usual work routine, but as I moved into the later trimesters, I began to delegate more responsibilities to my team. I wanted to ensure that I was not overwhelming myself, especially as I dealt with the physical changes and fatigue that can come with pregnancy. I communicated openly with my employees about my situation, and they were supportive, which helped create a positive work environment.

I also made it a point to stay organized and plan ahead for my maternity leave. I wanted to ensure that my business could continue to run smoothly while I took the necessary time off to focus on my new baby. I created a detailed plan outlining tasks and responsibilities that needed to be covered during my absence, and I trained my team to handle those duties.

Overall, while there were certainly moments of stress in juggling work and pregnancy, I felt fortunate to have the flexibility and support to manage both aspects of my life. If you’d like to know more about specific challenges I faced or how I prepared my business for my maternity leave, I’d be happy to share more details!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I certainly thought about the postpartum period and what it would mean for me and my family. I knew that adjusting to life with a newborn would bring its own set of challenges, and I wanted to be as prepared as possible.

One of my primary concerns was ensuring I had adequate support in place after the baby arrived. Given that I was a single mother, I planned to rely heavily on my family and friends. My parents were eager to help, and I knew they would be available to lend a hand, whether it was babysitting or just being there for emotional support. I also reached out to some close friends who had recently had babies to discuss their experiences and gather tips on managing the early days of motherhood.

I was aware that the postpartum period could be an emotional rollercoaster, so I planned to prioritize self-care. I intended to carve out time for myself, whether it was taking short breaks to relax or engaging in activities that brought me joy, like reading or going for walks. I recognized that managing my mental health would be just as important as taking care of the baby.

In terms of physical recovery, I discussed my postpartum plans with my healthcare provider during my prenatal appointments. They provided guidance on what to expect during recovery and the importance of monitoring my physical health, especially considering my type 2 diabetes. I planned to have follow-up appointments to ensure everything was healing properly and that I was managing my blood sugar levels effectively.

Additionally, I thought about how to balance my business responsibilities with motherhood. I knew I’d need to be flexible and prepared to adapt my work routine as needed. I started outlining a plan for how to ease back into my business while still being present for my newborn.

Overall, my goal was to approach the postpartum period with an open mind and flexibility, recognizing that it would be a time of adjustment. If you have specific questions about my postpartum plans or any particular aspects of that period that you’re interested in discussing, I’d be happy to share more!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
